PlatformSensorReaderWinrtBase::StartSensor() has

```
  if (!reading_callback_token_) {
    // Convert from frequency to interval in milliseconds since that is
    // what the Windows.Devices.Sensors API uses.
    unsigned int interval =
        (1 / configuration.frequency()) * base::Time::kMillisecondsPerSecond;

    auto hr = sensor_->put_ReportInterval(interval);
```

the `reading_callback_token_` check makes any further StartSensor() calls that occur when the optimal frequency changes in PlatformSensor::UpdateSensorInternal() not to do anything. In other words, as far as I can see once a PlatformSensorWin and an accompanying reader are created with a frequency, this frequency will be used until it is stopped. This doesn't affect the Win32 backend.
